Abandoned

in favor of shell tests

i did not manage to get it working with a wrapper script as per your example over here https://github.com/amboar/dbus-sensors/commit/deef99485d7671634baee09aac6368b8b839b574#diff-9cd49426232fe1cd89c98e67825def7724c31956a4e55ad5eabc84f466f05e32R14

Is the CI for that example also running with valgrind and asan?

For me, there were always errors with libasan.so complaining that it was not first in the link order.

The approach with execve works but is a bit hacky and i'm not happy with it.

Yeah, that series runs under the OpenBMC CI container. Can you could provide more details about what you tried or the logs of the errors?

Did you add the meson test setup support to deal with valgrind?

I think it's fixed now. Added

```
+  c_args: [
+    '-g',
+    '-fsanitize=address',
+  ],
+  link_args: [
+    '-fsanitize=address',
+  ],
```

and that helped. Previously i only had the -fsanitize=address in the c_args and
there were missing symbols at link time.
Done
Hi Alexander; there's quite a bit of infrastructure code to maintain here, and I feel much of it would go away if we exploited shell scripts a little more. I've left some comments inline.
This looks like `$RANDOM`. But do we actually want something random? Or just distinct from any other console ID?

I think it needs to be unique since meson could be running multiple instances of the same test.

Random was just an easy way to achieve that. It's not ideal since there is a low probability of collision.

What would you suggest? I see options like libuuid.
https://www.man7.org/linux/man-pages/man3/uuid.3.html
No, there's no need for libuuid. See my comment below about test names.
So this looks a lot like `grep -qF ...`

But ```grep -qF``` has like 0 readability.

I would have to look it up actually what these flags mean.
Unfamiliarity doesn't mean it's the wrong tool?
Acknowledged
and this looks a lot like `! grep -qF ...`

But ```grep -qF``` has like 0 readability.

Why system and why not `sd_bus_default()`?

```sd_bus_get_fd``` does not succeed in the console-server when i do that.

To me it looks like it is not allowed to re-use the bus connection in a child process like described here
https://www.freedesktop.org/software/systemd/man/latest/sd_bus_get_fd.html#

I think the AI described it pretty well:
```
To handle D-Bus connections using sd_bus_default() in both parent and child 
processes, you should avoid sharing the sd_bus connection and associated file 
descriptors across process boundaries. Instead, you should create a new sd_bus 
connection in the child process.


When you call sd_bus_default() in the parent process and then fork a child process, 
the file descriptors associated with the D-Bus connection are inherited by the 
child process, but the actual resources (context, etc.) are not safely shared. This 
is why sd_bus_get_fd() fails in the child process.

```

Reworked things so now the tests are creating the dbus connection in ```fork_off_console_server``` and the connection is released in the individual tests.

The d-bus connection is created after the child has been forked off so no d-bus resources are leaked to the child.
